Looking at your proposal, here are my initial notes:  This is a very cool idea. We need to carve out a MVP and a plan to iteratively roll out extra features. Roughly, I suggest starting with just signup/login, then create/read/update/delete budgets. That by itself is close to MVP. Then you can add expenses. Then payments to the budget. Then associate payments with expenses. Just an idea. Wireframes are very difficult to read. Please use consistently sized rectangles with solid background for pages, and use darker lines to make things more legible. The use of ovals for buttons is good, but then be consistent... don't use that for labels elsewhere. Labels probably shouldn't be in a box... it makes them look like an interactive element. ERD could use some consideration. What is the relationship between expenses and users? How about categories? Also, payments. We should discuss this.

Hey. Looking at your proposal, I think it's a good start, but needs some work. First, write more user stories. Every action a user can take (login, signup, and each CRUD operation, including viewing lists and record details) should have its own story. Second, the wireframes could use some clarification. Please put a rectangle to show input fields, and something to clearly indicate what is a button. User Submissions page, I can't tell what the content will look like when it's put on the page. Etc. Third, your ERD is looking good. There will need to be a users table, so add that. Also, is "generator" a data resource that will be stored in the DB?

in your ERD, don't add user_ or run_ before each property. You don't need those; that's implied within the context of the resource. consider the type of run time and type, and maybe distance. We should discuss how shoe mileage will work... is that a property to store in the shoe, or something calculated? Your stories aren't really organized into different actions. Basically, think about the CRUD operations and user login/signup. You have various stories that all relate to adding a run in the system. Nothing for editing or deleting a run, or adding a shoe. Etc. Your wireframes are on track, but also think about different types of screens. a form to add, a form to edit, a list view, a detail view, sign-up, etc. Also, it's a good convention to put labels as text and input fields as rectangular blocks, like they typically appear on screen.

Book3 Interview Feedback: Talking Out Loud:  Focus on verbalizing your thought process clearly during interviews. Remember, interviewers are often more interested in understanding how you approach problems than the final solution itself. Interview Framework  Use the suggested template as a guide:  Clarify: Ensure you understand the problem and ask questions to remove ambiguities. Plan: Outline your approach and write down key steps or pseudocode. Implement: Code your solution systematically. Test: Validate your solution with test cases. Optimize: Refactor or improve efficiency if time allows. You did an okay job planning in comments, but the execution stalled.  Implementation Challenges:  We didn’t get to implementing the algorithm due to difficulties in defining optional variables and confusion about the data structure. Next time, focus on breaking these steps into smaller, manageable tasks. Recommendation  Practice resolving similar problems on platforms like Pramp to improve communication and problem-solving skills in a realistic interview environment. Overall, while you showed potential, this would likely have been a "no hire" decision in a real interview. Working on these areas will significantly improve your performance.
